Small objects (≤ min_alloc_size) hurt RocksDB disproportionately. Because 1KB < min_alloc_size, the data is shoved inline into RocksDB values. You get zero 
data device savings from that, but you do concentrate all I/O onto the DB NVMe — compaction pressure on the DB device becomes the bottleneck, not the data HDD. 
This is why clusters handling many small objects should have oversized DB devices and aggressive bloom filter tuning.

Bucket index is the hidden amplifier. The rgw.buckets.index pool takes both a read and a write per PUT — and those omap entries in RocksDB are among the most 
compaction-heavy records at scale. Sharding the index (bucket_index_max_shards) reduces hotspot pressure but doesn't reduce the I/O count per operation.

The WAL is your latency hero. The ~24 synchronous physical IOPS in the immediate path are almost entirely sequential WAL writes on NVMe — which is why a 
good WAL device (Optane/P5800X class) has an outsized impact on small-object PUT latency compared to the data device.

Ops log doubles your log pool I/O. If you don't need per-request audit logging, disabling rgw_enable_ops_log removes 1 RADOS write
(3 physical OSD writes after replication) per PUT and meaningfully reduces log pool pressure.
